result.execSummary:
The defendant Harry Nyemah Jr was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Seek and maintain employment.  Be given job and vocational training.
Undergo a mental health evaluation.  Follow thru with any treatment recommended.

No contact with Evelyn M. or Monica L. or their residences.
No contact with the building located at 845 N. 26 Street, Milwaukee, WI.
No controlled substances other than those legally prescribed for defendant by a duly licensed physician for his mental or physical needs. Take all medications as prescribed and only for as long as deemed necessary for his mental or physical neds.
No alcohol.

Should defendant successfully  complete all conditions set forth by this Court and DOC, pay all costs assocaited with this case and remain free and clear of the criminal justice system arising to the level of probable cause or greater, misdemeanor or felony,  Court would consider petition for expungement.

Cognitive thinking intervention counseling.
Parenting classes/counseling.
AODA assessment. Treatment if needed.  Urine screens.
Pay the ordered surcharges, costs and disbursements. Failure to pay all monies at the end of probation period would result in a civil judgment entered against defendant.

records.addlTxt: Plea hearing proceeds.  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, and further advised that if not a United States citizen deportation is possible. Defendant sworn, examined as to plea, and entered a plea of guilty.  Court found defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived all constitutional rights. Plea questionnaire waiver of rights and addendum to plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulated to the criminal complaint as factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Amended Information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered into the record.  Due to the lateness in the hour, the Court was unable to proceed to sentencing at this time and ordered all terms and conditions of bail to continue.    Court ordered case adjourned for sentencing in Branch 20.  File retained in court.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for February 17, 2015 at 08:30 am
